title: Part 10
content:
Part 10

SOON AFTER, SHIRO dropped out. The last student disappeared.

From then on, my memories became more monotonous.

There was truly no one to talk to, and depending on the curriculum, there were days when I didn't open my mouth at all other than to mechanically ingest food.

Even though I was alone, my activities didn't change.

If anything had changed, it was probably related to all the aspects surrounding martial arts.

Until now, I had competed with other White Room students, but now that there were no more. All my opponents inevitably became adults.

By the time I was nine years old, I had defeated all the instructors who had taught me everything about martial arts.

That was probably why the instructors were gathered in the room in a hurried manner this time.

"Kiyotaka, from now on, you will fight multiple people in actual combat format. You can consider it the culmination of everything you've learned. You're allowed to use any means necessary."

"Yes."

"And you don't need to hold back at all. You can go as far as killing."

"Are you saying it's okay to actually kill someone?"

"As long as we don't stop you, you can take it literally. Be very careful."

"Yes."

Adults in suits entered a spacious room designed for training.

All the faces were new to me.

When the adults spotted me, they started laughing with silly expressions.

"I thought it was a joke, but here we are, being told to fight this kid seriously."

The adults I had previously seen, the ones who had taught martial arts, were clearly different from them.

Their movements weren't fluid, but rough and spirited.

It seemed they were capable of unconventional fighting in a setting with dramatic shifts rather than a flat one.

Just like before, I couldn't possibly compete with them in terms of pure physical strength.

The difference in muscle mass was clear.

If I clashed head-on, I would lose all one hundred out of one hundred times.

"It's ridiculous, yes, but don't hold back. They're offering a huge sum just to subdue one child. You better think of him as someone with unimaginable skills."

The person who spoke was a man who seemed to have authority among them.

"Listen. Come at us intending to kill. No, try to kill us. Without that level of spirit and resolve, I'd feel somewhat guilty knocking you down."

The apparent leader instructed me as such.

I didn't need to be told; I had already received the orders.

"We'll provide some weapons if necessary."

With that, he placed the shoes he had brought on the ground.[1]

The sound of metal scraping echoed from the floor.

"I don't need them."

"You're going to fight with your bare hands?"

"Yes."

"You're not joking… We're serious too. Just choose."

"Instructor, is that an order?"

I looked up at the instructor on the second floor for guidance.

"It's an order. Do as the man says. You should already be familiar with everything."

If that's the case, I'll just comply.

I peered into the bag.

"Choose whatever you like: a baton, a stun gun, or a knife."

Indeed, I had seen, held, and learned how to use all of these in past lessons.

If I focused on lethality, a knife would do, but I wanted reach.

"I'll take this."

Without hesitation, I reached for the baton and grabbed it.

The collapsed baton was about thirty centimeters long.

"Do you know how to use it?"

"Swing it and it'll extend to about thirty centimeters. Then, I hit my opponent with it, right?"

"That's right."

To win, I had to accurately target human vital points.

The opponent probably didn't have any experience fighting someone my build.

I needed to take advantage of being short and small, which would make me difficult to confront.

A few minutes later, as the last adult fell with his leg shattered by the baton, I raised my weapon. I aimed to knock him out with one blow to the head.

If that didn't work, I would just need to smash his skull with a second strike.

"STOP! STOP!"

Hearing the voice echo in the room, I stopped what I was doing and gently threw the baton away.

Adults hurried into the room and helped the fallen men up.

"What the hell… We need to get them to the infirmary immediately!"

The medical team, realizing the severity of their condition, carried them out on a stretcher.

"What is the meaning of this, Kiyotaka?"

"I was ordered to kill."

To confirm it, I even asked again if it was really okay.

What's the problem with that?

The instructors were stunned by the situation, but then the door to the room opened.

"A-Ayanokouji-sensei!?"

"You guys take care of these people. I want to have a little meeting with Kiyotaka. Follow me."

The order was absolute.

I followed without a hint of hesitation.

Usually, there would be several instructors with him, but today, it seemed he was alone.

"You probably understand by now, but I am the head of the White Room, and I'm also your biological father."

"I know."

"I never directly claimed to be your father. When did you realize it?"

"When I was four. I remember hearing it while the instructors were talking."

"I see. As a fourth-generation student, you have continued to achieve overwhelming results. Before I knew it, you were the only one left, silently completing the curriculum perfectly… no, surpassing it."

A father—to me, that was nothing special.

It was just a fact that he was my father. Nothing more, nothing less.

"You are special to me."

"…"

"The White Room has only been in operation for about fourteen or fifteen years, but even so, I can't envision another genius like you emerging in the next few years. From the first to the third-generation children, not to mention, most of the fifth-generation children and beyond have similar tendencies. Of course, with each generation, they are steadily reducing their flaws and overcoming challenges…"

It seemed like he was praising me.

However, like the talk about my father, it was just a fact.

"You may go back now."

"If you'll excuse me."

What was the meaning of this conversation?

It probably had something to do with the device attached to my arm.

Supporting that idea, the man continued speaking.

"How did it go?"

"Even during the fight, and in your conversation with him, Ayanokouji-sensei, there was barely any disturbance in Kiyotaka's pulse or anything like that."

"Even when he's called a special existence, his heart doesn't stir at all, huh? No, it seems his human emotions have completely ceased functioning."

"That is both Kiyotaka's strength and a permanent weakness."

"Ishida is right. Having minimal emotions is fine, but emotions are still essential. It would've been enough even if he only had half as much as an ordinary person, but in Kiyotaka's case, he has almost nothing. Whether as an educator, a politician, or anything else, he's both suited and unsuited for the role, huh?"

In front of the person in question himself, the two spoke openly about various things.

This might also be part of the curriculum.

Whether I was praised or criticized, it didn't matter.

Everything comes down to whether you drop out—that's all.

"It's probably impossible to instill emotions like joy, anger, sorrow, and pleasure in the White Room environment."

"Yes. However, he can skillfully lie when he needs to. Although he lacks emotions, you could say that he's learned how to appropriately disguise himself."

"That's exactly the problem. It's too late to instill emotions in the White Room now. If so, we have no choice but to significantly change his environment."

"…I don't understand."

"You don't get it?"

"From the first generation to the current first-year students, I've educated many children. The curriculum difficulty has varied greatly, but Ayanokouji Kiyotaka is clearly an anomaly. This isn't just favoritism because he's your son. It's abnormal."

"Indeed, that's true. No matter how harsh the environment is, Kiyotaka soon adapts. While every other child has a limit, why is Kiyotaka the only one that doesn't? No matter how much he's taught, why is he able to absorb everything?"

"I don't know… It's easy to dismiss it as atavism, but without pursuing the phenomenon, the White Room will never be truly complete."

"If we can consistently provide people with equal or greater abilities than this child, my ideal will be realized. Thoroughly investigate it. Don't dive up thinking until you understand. I'm paying you enough for that."

I continued receiving education. What awaited at the end of it, what laid beyond the pursuit of knowledge—

I wanted to know just that.

  1. [1]: In most Japanese martial arts, people take their shoes off. The shoes have nothing to do with the weapons.
